        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Magistratus Romani, pro Reip[ublicae] vtilitate; non pro dignitate Priuatarum Personarum. pro se quisq[ue]: et qui non possunt esse 
                        foris Scipiones, domi esse volunt Petilij: audentes eos vexare cauillando, quos non audent benè merendo a[e]mulari.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Scipio Aemilianus"/>
                    <person name="Scipio Africanus"/>
                    <person name="Quintus Petillius Cerialis"/> 
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                The Roman offices served the use of the republic, not the grandeur of individual persons. Every one for himself, and those who cannot be 
                Scipios abroad, want to be Petiliuses at home. And they have the nerve to taunt those by quibbling who they do not dare to rival by deserving 
                well.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Ingrata Scipionibus Roma: nec a[e]dificant Africani, et Asiatici gloriosa cognomina, sine altioribus, firmioribusq[ue] fundamentis 
                        stabilita[e] magnitudinis. Licuisset Scipionibus esse potentioribus, si suu[m] statu[m] priuatis opibus, publicisq[ue] amicitijs validè 
                        fundatum, qua
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Scipio Aemilianus"/> 
                    <person name="Scipio Africanus"/>
                    <person name="Lucius Cornelius Scipio Asiaticus"/>
                </position>
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>possent Auctoritate muniuissent. Deficiunt homines, nisi cogantur vinculis, aut teneantur beneficijs.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Rome is ungrateful to the Scipios; but the Africanuses and Asiaticuses do not create their illustrious eponyms without very deep and steady 
                foundations of firmly established greatness. The Scipios could have been more powerful, if they had buttressed their position, based strongly 
                on private means and public relations, as much as they could with authority. People defect, unless they are forced by chains or kept by 
                favours.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Disciplina[e] militaris solidus validusq[ue] vsus in Rep[ublica]. Duros dura faciunt: molles mollia. Assuescere oportet inuictos: 
                        nec vnq[uam] languescere. 
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                The firm and powerful use of military training in the Republic. Hard measures make hard men; soft ones make soft men. It is right for the 
                invincible to get used to it and never to grow weak.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
